@node NEWF "Project/ New ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ New ģ@{FG Text}

This command allows you to create new font outlines and metrics. Font
outlines and metrics are started independently.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before creating a
font metric.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.

See also:
@{" New ģ Outline " link NEWO}
@{" New ģ Metrics " link NEWM}
@prev QUIT
@endnode

@node NEWO "Project/ New ģ Outline..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ New ģ Outline...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester to set the general attributes for a new
font. The requester is identical to that opened by the @{"Font Attributes" link TypeSmith:Help/English/edi/ATTR}
command. Font attributes can be set at any time so you can change any or
all of the settings at a later time.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Attribute@{UU}: Sets the attribute for DMF fonts.

@{U}Font ID@{UU}: Unique identification number.

@{U}FontName@{UU}: Name of the font without spaces. i.e.,
AGaramond-Semibold

@{U}FamilyName@{UU}: Name of the font family. i.e., AdobeGaramond

@{U}Weight@{UU}: Name of the weight in a family. i.e., Semibold

@{U}FullName@{UU}: Complete name of the font with spaces. i.e., Adobe
Garamond Semibold

@{U}Notice@{UU}: Used for copyright or author's notices. Up to 106
characters.

@{U}Underline@{UU}: Sets the underline offset from the baseline. Default =
-150.

@{U}Thickness@{UU}: Sets the underline thickness. Default = 20.

@{U}FixedPitch@{UU}: Makes all characters an equal width.

@{U}Version@{UU}: Used for the version number of your font.
@endnode

@node NEWM "Project/ New ģ Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ New ģ Metrics...@{FG Text}

This commands opens a requester to configure the metric generation
process. (Font metric refers to character widths, spacing and @{"kerning" link TypeSmith:Help/English/sub/KERN}.)
If there is already font metric information for the current font outline,
you will be prompted if you want to delete the metric information to start
a new metrics file.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Constant Numeral Spacing@{UU}: Makes all numerals the same width,
based on the widest numeral.

@{U}Space Character Width@{UU}: Specifies the width of the space character
(32).

@{U}Character Tracking@{UU}: Controls character widths. The metric
generation process calculates each character's right side bearing by
multiplying the width of the character outline by the tracking value, and
then adds the left side bearing, right side bearing, and character outline
width to get the overall width.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before creating a
font metric.
@endnode

@node NEWW "Project/ New Window"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ New Window@{FG Text}

This commands opens another character window for the current font. You can
use this command to view more than one character at once, or to view the
same character in different view modes.
@endnode

@node OPEN "Project/ Open ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Open ģ@{FG Text}

This allows you to open existing font outlines and metrics. Font outlines
and metrics are opened independently with the two subcommands. Only
Soft-Logik format fonts may be opened; other formats must be interpreted
with the @{"Import" link IMPO} command.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before opening a
font metric file.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.

See also:
@{" Open ģ Outline " link OPEO}
@{" Open ģ Metrics " link OPEM}
@endnode

@node OPEO "Project/ Open ģ Outline..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Open ģ Outline...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a DMF outline file to
open. Only Soft-Logik DMF outline files may be opened; other formats must
be interpreted with the @{"Import" link IMPO} command.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.
@endnode

@node OPEM "Project/ Open ģ Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Open ģ Metrics...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a FM metrics file to
open. Only Soft-Logik FM metric files may be opened; other formats must be
interpreted with the @{"Import" link IMPO} command.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before opening a
font metric file.
@endnode

@node CLOS "Project/ Close"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Close@{FG Text}

This command closes the current font and all its windows.

@endnode

@node SAVE "Project/ Save ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save ģ@{FG Text}

This allows you to save the current font outline and/or metric. Font
outlines and metrics are saved independently with the two subcommands.
This command saves fonts in the Soft-Logik outline font format. Other
formats must be saved with the @{"Export" link EXPO} command.

See also:
@{" Save ģ Outline " link SAVO}
@{" Save ģ Metrics " link SAVM}
@endnode

@node SAVO "Project/ Save ģ Outline"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save ģ Outline@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font outline in DMF format with its current
name. If the font is untitled, this command will open a ASL file requester
to name the font outline file.
@endnode

@node SAVM "Project/ Save ģ Metric"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save ģ Metric@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font metric in FM format with its current
name. If the font is untitled, this command will open an ASL file
requester to name the font metric file.
@endnode

@node SAVA "Project/ Save As ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save As ģ@{FG Text}

This allows you to save the current font outline and/or metric with a new
name or path. Font outlines and metrics are saved independently with the
two subcommands. This command saves fonts in the Soft-Logik outline font
format. Other formats must be saved with the @{"Export" link EXPO} command.

See also:
@{" Save As ģ Outline " link SAAO}
@{" Save As ģ Metrics " link SAAM}
@endnode

@node SAAO "Project/ Save As ģ Outline"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save As ģ Outline@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to save the current font outline
in DMF format with a new name or path.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before saving a
font outline.
@endnode

@node SAAM "Project/ Save As ģ Metric"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Save As ģ Metric@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to save the current font metric
in FM format with a new name or path.

You must have an active window containing a font outline and metric before
saving a font metric.
@endnode

@node IMPO "Project/ Import ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ@{FG Text}

This allows you to import existing font outlines and metrics in PostScript
Type 1 and Compugraphic Intellifont formats. IFF DR2D drawings may also be
imported into the current character window.

Soft-Logik format fonts should be opened with the @{"Open" link OPEN}
command.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before importing
a font metric file. Compugraphic Intellifonts include the outline and
metric in one file so there is no need to open separate outline and metric
files.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.

See also:
@{" Import ģ Compugraphic Intellifont      " link ICOM}
@{" Import ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline " link IPFB}
@{" Import ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics " link IAFM}
@{" Import ģ PFM Windows Metrics           " link IPFM}
@{" Import ģ IFF DR2D Drawing              " link IIFF}
@endnode

@node ICOM "Project/ Import ģ Compugraphic Intellifont..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ Compugraphic Intellifont...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a Compugraphic
Intellifont to import. Since these fonts have only one font file (.type or
.lib), the entire font will be loaded at once.

Compugraphic fonts can have up to 65,535 characters. When a Compugraphic
font is loaded, its characters will be mapped as closely as possible to
the TypeSmith and Soft-Logik Outline format encoding set. Most have 255
characters or less, so this is not normally a problem.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.
@endnode

@node IPFB "Project/ Import ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a MS-DOS format
PostScript Type 1 PFB outline file to import. The font metric (AFM) file
must be imported separately after importing the outline.

If the font does not use Adobe Standard Encoding or TypeSmith encoding,
TypeSmith will ask you whether to load it with TypeSmith encoding.

The maximum number of open fonts is 5.
@endnode

@node IAFM "Project/ Import ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a MS-DOS format
PostScript Type 1 AFM metric file to import.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before opening a
font metric file.
@endnode

@node IPFM "Project/ Import ģ PFM Windows Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ PFM Windows Metrics...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a Windows format
PostScript Type 1 PFM metric file to import.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before opening a
font metric file.
@endnode

@node IIFF "Project/ Import ģ IFF DR2D Drawing..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ IFF DR2D Drawing...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to select a drawing file to
import. The file must be in IFF DR2D format.

The drawing will be stored in the clipboard and the mouseform will change
to a picture frame shape to help you position the drawing. Position the
picture frame at the top left corner of the area at which to paste the
drawing, and then click the mouse button.

Drawings may be pasted at a different size than the original by dragging
the mouse while pasting. While you drag the mouse you will see a box which
represents the size of the drawing. If you hold down a Shift key while
sizing the drawing, the original aspect ratio will be maintained.

Pasting does not erase the clipboard's contents. You can paste multiple
copies of the drawing by repeatedly choosing the Paste command.

IFF DR2D supports many more drawing options than those used by fonts. When
you import, a drawing groups will be ungrouped, and line styles, fill
styles and colors will be deleted. Text objects which are not converted to
graphics before saving in IFF DR2D will be ignored when imported.

All paths in an imported drawing will become subpaths of the character,
since fonts do not allow parts of characters to be merged separately.
@endnode

@node EXPO "Project/ Export ģ"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Export ģ@{FG Text}

This allows you to export the current font outline and/or metric in
PostScript Type 1, Type 3 or Compugraphic Intellifont formats. IFF DR2D
drawings may also be exported from the current character window.

Soft-Logik format fonts should be saved with the @{"Save" link SAVE} or @{"Save As" link SAVA} commands.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before exporting
a font outline, and there must be font metric information for that font
before exporting a font metric file. Compugraphic Intellifonts include the
outline and metric in one file so there must be font metric information
before exporting an Intellifont.

See also:
@{" Export ģ Compugraphic Intellifont      " link ECOM}
@{" Export ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline " link EPFB}
@{" Export ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics " link EAFM}
@{" Export ģ PostScript Type 3             " link EPS3}
@{" Export ģ IFF DR2D Drawing              " link EIFF}
@remark {" Export ģ PFM Windows Metrics           " link EPFM} Not currently implemented!
@endnode

@node ECOM "Project/ Export ģ Compugraphic Intellifont..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Export ģ Compugraphic Intellifont...@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font outline and metric in Compugraphic
Intellifont format. If you have not specified a unique font ID in
@{"Font Attributes" link TypeSmith:Help/English/edi/ATTR}, TypeSmith will ask if you want
to export the font anyway.

It first opens a requester to set Compugraphic options. Generally, these
settings are not used by amiga applications. Change your settings from the
defaults if desired. This requester also allows you to generate the
.metric and .dat files required by Professional Page and Professional
Draw, and to generate automatic font @{"hints" link TypeSmith:Help/English/sub/HINT}. After clicking on Save, an
ASL file requester will open to set the name and path of the file to save.

You must have an active window containing a font outline and metric before
exporting an Intellifont.

Note: Due to a limitation in AmigaDOS, you cannot export Intellifonts
directly to fonts:_bullet_outlines. Export them to another directory and
then use the Intellifont (Workbench 3) or Fountain (Workbench 2) programs
to install them in fonts:_bullet_outlines.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Create .dat and .metric files for Gold DiskŽ programs@{UU}: Use for
Professional Page 3.0+, Professional Draw 3.0+ and PageSetter III.

@{U}Generate Hints@{UU}: Export with Intellifont hints.
@endnode

@node EPFB "Project/ Export ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ PFB PostScript Type 1 Outline...@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font outline in MS-DOS PostScript Type 1
PFB format. If you have not specified a unique font ID in @{"Font Attributes" link TypeSmith:Help/English/edi/ATTR},
TypeSmith will ask if you want to export the font anyway.

It first opens a requester to specify Adobe Standard Encoding or TypeSmith
Encoding, and to generate automatic font @{"hints" link TypeSmith:Help/English/sub/HINT}. After clicking on Save,
an ASL file requester will open to set the name and path of the file to
save.

You must have an active window containing a font outline before exporting
a PFB file.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Encoding Type@{UU}: Choose the the encoding system type.

@{U}Generate Hints@{UU}: Export with PostScript hints.
@endnode

@node EAFM "Project/ Export ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ AFM PostScript Type 1 Metrics...@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font metric in MS-DOS PostScript Type 1 AFM
format. If you have not specified a unique font ID in @{"Font Attributes" link TypeSmith:Help/English/edi/ATTR},
TypeSmith will ask if you want to export the font anyway.

The command opens an ASL file requester to set the name and path of the
file to save.

You must have an active window containing a font outline and metric before
exporting an AFM file.
@next EPS3
@endnode

@node EPFM "Project/ Export ģ PFM Windows Metrics..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Import ģ PFM Windows Metrics...@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font metric in Windows PostScript Type 1
PFM format. If you have not specified a unique font ID in @{"Font Attributes" link TypeSmith:Help/English/edi/ATTR},
TypeSmith will ask if you want to export the font anyway.

The command opens an ASL file requester to set the name and path of the
file to save.

You must have an active window containing a font outline and metric before
exporting an AFM file.

NOTE: THIS COMMAND IS NOT CURRENTLY IMPLEMENTED.
@endnode

@node EPS3 "Project/ Export ģ PostScript Type 3..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Export ģ PostScript Type 3...@{FG Text}

This command saves the current font outline in MS-DOS PostScript Type 3
format. The command opens an ASL file requester will open to set the name
and path of the file to save.

You must have an active window containing a font outline and metric before
exporting a PFB file.

Note: PostScript Type 3 fonts cannot have spaces in their names. TypeSmith
will convert spaces to dashes in names if you save a font with a space in
its name.
@prev EAFM
@endnode

@node EIFF "Project/ Export ģ IFF DR2D Drawing..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Export ģ IFF DR2D Drawing...@{FG Text}

This command opens an ASL file requester to export the selected paths as
an IFF DR2D drawing.

TypeSmith saves drawings as filled, but unstroked. All paths in a
character are merged into a single path so that they will appear properly
filled when imported into another program.
@endnode

@node PRNT "Project/ Print Preview..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Print Preview...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester to set print options. TypeSmith allows you
to preview characters on your printer. Only the character in the active
character window will be printed. TypeSmith can print to any Preferences
compatible printer. Ensure that you select the correct Preferences driver
and that your printer is connected and online before printing.

@{FG Highlight}Requester Gadgets:@{FG Text}

@{U}Printer Driver@{UU}: Shows the driver selected with Preferences. It
cannot be changed from within TypeSmith.

@{U}Resolution@{UU}: Choose the output resolution. The resolution options
are dependent on the driver selected.

@{U}Orientation@{UU}: Select portrait (vertical) or landscape (horizontal)
orientation for the output.

@{U}Character Size@{UU}: Sets the character size in points.

@{U}Outline Only@{UU}: Print characters unfilled.

@{U}Center@{UU}: Centers the output on the page.

@{U}Negative@{UU}: Prints characters in reverse type.
@endnode

@node INFO "Project/ Info..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Info...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester that lists program statistics. The Max
Magnification is the maximum view magnification, give the @{"MAXFACTOR" link TypeSmith:Help/English/tty/MAXFACTOR}
tool type setting. The Number of Character Windows lists how many
character windows are currently open. The Number of Points states how many
fonts and windows are open, and how points are in the paths in the active
character window.
@endnode

@node ABOU "Project/ About TypeSmith..."

@{FG Highlight}Project/ About TypeSmith...@{FG Text}

This command opens a requester that provides useful information concerning
the free memory in your computer.
@endnode

@node QUIT "Project/ Quit"

@{FG Highlight}Project/ Quit@{FG Text}

This command exits TypeSmith. If a font has not been saved, you will be
prompted before the program exits.
@next NEWF
@endnode
